\begin_layout Standard
This section outlines the baseline model,
 which extends the framework of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/aer.98.3.690"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The decision maker is a government of a small open economy that borrows from risk-neutral foreign creditors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A small open economy is endowed with an exogenous stochastically fluctuating potential output stream 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 The logarithm of potential output,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(y_{t})$
\end_inset

,
 follows a first-order autoregressive (AR(1)) process:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln(y_{t+1})=\rho\ln(y_{t})+\varepsilon_{t+1},\quad\text{where }\varepsilon_{t+1}\sim N(0,\sigma_{\varepsilon}^{2})\label{eq:ar1_y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the level of potential output,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the persistence parameter (e.g.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\rho|<1$
\end_inset

),
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 is an i.i.d.
 normal shock with mean zero and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\varepsilon}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The process for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 implies a transition probability kernel for the level of output,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y,y')$
\end_inset

.
 Potential output 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is realized only in periods in which the government honors its sovereign debt.
 The output good can be traded or consumed.
 Households within the country are identical and rank stochastic consumption streams according to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}_{0}\left[\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}u\left(c_{t}\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(·\right)$
\end_inset

 is an increasing and strictly concave utility function.
 Household consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is affected by the government’s international borrowing and lending decisions.
 Because households are averse to consumption fluctuations,
 the government will try to smooth consumption by borrowing from (and lending to) foreign creditors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Asset Market 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only credit instrument available to the government is a one-period bond traded in international credit markets.
 The bond market has the following features:
 first,
 the bond matures in one period and is not state contingent.
 Second,
 a purchase of bonds with total face value 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 (a claim to 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 units of the consumption good next period) costs 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y)B'$
\end_inset

 today,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y)$
\end_inset

 is the price of a bond promising one unit of face value next period,
 given current state 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and chosen next period assets 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

.
 Third,
 if the government issues bonds (i.e.,
 borrows,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B'<0$
\end_inset

),
 it sells a promise to repay 
\begin_inset Formula $-B'$
\end_inset

 units next period (note that 
\begin_inset Formula $-B'$
\end_inset

 is a positive quantity).
 For this,
 it receives 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y)(-B')$
\end_inset

 units of the good today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Earnings on the government portfolio are distributed (or,
 if negative,
 taxed) lump sum to households.
 When the government is not excluded from financial markets,
 the one-period national budget constraint is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{t}=y_{t}+B_{t}-q\left(B_{t+1},y_{t}\right)B_{t+1}.\label{eq:budget_cons}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To rule out Ponzi schemes,
 we also require that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}\ge-Z$
\end_inset

 in every period where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is an exogenous borrowing upper bound.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is chosen to be sufficiently large that the constraint never binds in equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Financial Markets 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are risk-neutral foreign creditors who know the domestic output stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

and observe 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{s}\right\} _{s=0}^{t}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The creditors can borrow or lend without limit in an international credit market at a constant risk-free rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The creditors receive full payment if the government chooses to pay and receive 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 if the government defaults on its one-period debt due.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the government is expected to default on obligations due at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y_{t})$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 is the chosen bond position for 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the output at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

),
 the expected value of a promise to pay one unit of consumption next period is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\delta(B',y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 the bond price 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y)$
\end_inset

 for a promise to pay one unit of consumption next period is given by its discounted expected value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q\left(B',y\right)=\frac{1-\delta\left(B',y\right)}{1+r}.\label{eq:qdelta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of default next period,
 conditional on choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 today when current output is 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The key is to determine the default probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Decision on default
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 the government chooses between defaulting and meeting its current obligations and purchasing or selling an optimal quantity of one-period sovereign debt.
 Defaulting means declining to pay all of its current obligations.
 Default triggers two consequences:
 first,
 the output is decreased from 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(y_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le h\left(y_{t}\right)\le y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance,
 
\begin_inset Formula $h(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 could take the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\min(\psi\bar{y},y_{t})$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 represents a reference output level (such as the long-run average output).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output returns to normal only after the sovereign regains access to international credit markets.
 Second,
 the sovereign loses access to foreign credit markets.
 While in a state of default,
 the economy regains access to foreign credit in each subsequent period with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Government's Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Default
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 be the value function of government in default,
 the government has only one state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and facing the recursion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V^{D}\left(y\right)=u\left(h\left(y\right)\right)+\beta\mathbb{E}_{y'}\left[\theta V\left(0,y'\right)+\left(1-\theta\right)V^{D}\left(y'\right)|y\right].\label{eq:val_default}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the continuation value,
 the government either regain credit market access with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 debt with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 or stay in default and gain 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}\left(y'\right)$
\end_inset

 next period with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Repay
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the government stays in credit market at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and chooses to repay,
 then it choose a control variable 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 to maximize the value of repayment.
 The Bellman equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}V^{R}\left(B,y\right) & =\max_{B'}\left\{ u\left(c\right)+\beta\mathbb{E}_{y'}\left[V\left(B',y'\right)|y\right]\right\} \\
\text{s.t. \ensuremath{\quad}}c & =y+B-q\left(B',y\right)B'\\
B & \ge-Z
\end{aligned}
,\label{eq:val_repay}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(B',y'\right)$
\end_inset

 is the optimal value of the government's problem when facing the choice of whether to repay or default at the beginning of the next period with state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(B',y'\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The government chooses to default if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}\left(y\right)>V^{R}\left(B,y\right)$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(B,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by the maximum of the two values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(B,y\right)=\max\left\{ V^{R}\left(B,y\right),V^{D}\left(y\right)\right\} .\label{eq:val_all}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Default probability with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

- rationality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the value function,
 global lenders can now evaluate the probability of default and therefore give the price function 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(B',y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Unlike 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/aer.98.3.690"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where all lenders are rational in comparing the next period value,
 I introduce a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 to denote the fraction of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rational
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 lenders.
 For the rational lenders,
 they predict the default decision of all possible next period output level 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 and then formulate expectation of default next period given 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\delta_{r}\left(B',y\right) & =\mathbb{E}_{y'}\left[\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ V^{D}\left(y'\right)>V^{R}\left(B',y'\right)\right\} }|y\right]\\
 & =\int\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ V^{D}\left(y'\right)>V^{R}\left(B',y'\right)\right\} }p\left(y,y'\right)\mathrm{d}y'
\end{aligned}
,\label{eq:delta_r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ A\right\} }$
\end_inset

 is the indicator function of condition 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda)$
\end_inset

 fraction of "boundedly rational" lenders,
 they evaluate the default decision based on a point expectation of next period's output,
 conditional on current output 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically,
 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(y)$
\end_inset

 follows the AR(1) process in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ar1_y"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 these lenders form their expectation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textit{level}$
\end_inset

 of next period's output,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}'=\exp(E[\ln(y')|\ln(y)])=\exp(\rho\ln(y))$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 denotes the current level of output,
 this forecast can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\rho}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 for a given next period bond position 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

,
 these lenders formulate the probability of default as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\delta_{ir}\left(B',y\right) & =\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ V^{D}\left(\mathbb{E}\left[y'|y\right]\right)>V^{R}\left(B',\mathbb{E}\left[y'|y\right]\right)\right\} }\\
 & =\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ V^{D}\left(y^{\rho}\right)>V^{R}\left(B',y^{\rho}\right)\right\} }
\end{aligned}
.\label{eq:delta_ir}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given the fraction of rational lenders 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

,
 the total probability of default next period perceived by the global lenders is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\delta\left(B',y;\lambda\right) & =\lambda\delta_{r}\left(B',y\right)+\left(1-\lambda\right)\delta_{ir}\left(B',y\right)\\
 & =\lambda\int\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ V^{D}\left(y'\right)>V^{R}\left(B',y'\right)\right\} }p\left(y,y'\right)\mathrm{d}y'+\left(1-\lambda\right)\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ V^{D}\left(y^{\rho}\right)>V^{R}\left(B',y^{\rho}\right)\right\} }
\end{aligned}
.\label{eq:delta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given zero profits for foreign creditors in equilibrium,
 we can combine 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:qdelta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
