name "sec:theoretical_results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before proceeding to the quantitative analysis,
 I briefly establish that several key theoretical properties from the standard sovereign default model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/aer.98.3.690"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 continue to hold in my framework with boundedly rational lenders.
 The primary purpose of this section is to verify the robustness of the model's basic mechanics.
 First,
 I define the default set,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(B)$
\end_inset

,
 as the set of output realizations 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for which default is the optimal policy given an initial asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{D}(B)=\{y\mid V^{D}(y)>V^{R}(B,y)\}.
\]

\end_inset

The following propositions characterize the equilibrium default policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:default_assets"

\end_inset

 The incentive to default is non-increasing with the government's net asset position.
 For any two asset levels 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}\leq B_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 if default is optimal with asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

 at some output level 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 then default is also optimal with asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 at the same output level 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Formally,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(B_{2})\subseteq\mathcal{D}(B_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proof-for-Proposition 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof is standard and follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The introduction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-rationality affects the level of the bond price schedule 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\cdot)$
\end_inset

,
 but not the monotonicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}$
\end_inset

 with respect to current assets 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:default_assets"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 establishes that default becomes more attractive as the government's balance sheet deteriorates.
 The next proposition shows that once debt reaches a level where default becomes a possibility,
 the government faces an endogenous borrowing constraint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:no_inflow"

\end_inset

 If,
 for some asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 the default set is non-empty,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(B)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

,
 then there are no contracts 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q(B',y),B'\}$
\end_inset

 chosen in equilibrium such that the economy can experience a capital inflow.
 That is,
 any equilibrium choice must satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $B-q(B',y;\lambda)B'\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proof-for-Proposition2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof follows the logic in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/aer.98.3.690"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 demonstrating that any equilibrium price offered to a risky sovereign must be inconsistent with the condition required for a net capital inflow.
 Our 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-rationality mechanism alters the precise equilibrium price but does not invalidate this fundamental no-free-lunch condition.
 Finally,
 we establish that default is a response to adverse economic conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:default_income-1"

\end_inset

 The incentive to default is stronger for lower levels of current endowment.
 For any given asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 if it is optimal to default at an output level 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 it is also optimal to default at any output level 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\le y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Formally,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}\in\mathcal{D}(B)$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\in\mathcal{D}(B)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proof-for-Proposition 3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result holds because the marginal value of income is higher when the government maintains market access than when it is in default.
 Access to credit markets allows for better intertemporal smoothing,
 making the continuation value under repayment more sensitive to positive income shocks.
 Taken together,
 these propositions confirm that my model with boundedly rational lenders preserves the core theoretical structure of the canonical sovereign default model.
 Default remains a state-contingent decision that occurs when the country is highly indebted and experiences a negative output shock.
 This verification of the model's basic properties is crucial,
 as it provides a stable foundation upon which I can analyze the novel effects of my central mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theoretical Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:discontinuity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established that the standard mechanics are intact,
 the analysis can now move beyond them.
 I establish the main theoretical contribution of this paper in this section,
 demonstrating how this heterogeneity in lender beliefs fundamentally reshapes the credit market by introducing sharp,
 endogenous discontinuities into the bond price schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Price Drop
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theoretical contribution of this paper stems from a novel non-linearity introduced by the assumption of boundedly rational lenders.
 I establish the model's main theoretical result:
 when a fraction of lenders form expectations irrationally (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<1$
\end_inset

),
 the otherwise smooth bond price schedule of the standard model is replaced by one that exhibits a sharp,
 endogenous discontinuity.
 This result is formalized in the following theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:price_drop"

\end_inset

 With a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda)>0$
\end_inset

 of boundedly rational lenders,
 the equilibrium bond price schedule 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;\lambda)$
\end_inset

 exhibits a unique discontinuity at a critical debt threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically,
 the following properties hold:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The price function drops discontinuously at the threshold:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{B'\to\tilde{B}'(y)^{+}}q(B',y;\lambda)-\lim_{B'\to\tilde{B}'(y)^{-}}q(B',y;\lambda)=\frac{1-\lambda}{1+r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $B'\in(\tilde{B}'(y),0]$
\end_inset

,
 the price is 
\series bold
weakly higher
\series default
 than the full rationality benchmark:
 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;\lambda)\ge q(B',y;1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $B'<\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

,
 the price is 
\series bold
weakly lower
\series default
 than the full rationality benchmark:
 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;\lambda)\le q(B',y;1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proof-for-Theorem1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The economic intuition behind Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:price_drop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 lies in the abrupt shift in the beliefs of boundedly rational lenders.
 Their assessment of default risk 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:delta_ir"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 acts as a step function.
 For low levels of debt,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B'>\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

),
 the value of repayment at the expected future output,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B',y^{\rho})$
\end_inset

,
 is high.
 Consequently,
 these lenders perceive zero default risk (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ir}=0$
\end_inset

).
 Their presence dilutes the concerns of rational lenders over low-probability tail events,
 leading to an aggregate market perception of lower risk and thus a higher bond price compared to the fully rational benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This market optimism,
 however,
 is fragile.
 From Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:default_assets"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B',y^{\rho})$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing function of the debt level.
 As the government proposes to take on more debt,
 it eventually crosses the critical threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

 where the value of repayment falls below the value of default at the expected output level.
 At this precise point,
 the boundedly rational lenders' risk assessment flips immediately from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 This causes a discrete upward jump in the aggregate default probability,
 which in turn triggers a discontinuous drop in the bond price and therefore leads to a price drop.
 For all debt levels beyond this threshold,
 the market becomes systematically more PRO-biased than the fully rational benchmark,
 as the strong PRO beliefs of the boundedly rational agents (who now see default as certain) weigh down the average price.
 This discontinuity can be interpreted as a crisis threshold in the credit market,
 driven entirely by the heterogeneity of lender expectations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equilibrium Interest Rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This price discontinuity has a direct consequence on the interest rates the sovereign faces in equilibrium.
 I define the equilibrium interest rate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{c}(B,y)$
\end_inset

,
 as the rate implied by the government's optimal bond choice at state 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,y)$
\end_inset

,
 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $B'(B,y)$
\end_inset

.
 Formally,
 it is given by:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r^{c}(B,y)=\frac{1}{q(B'(B,y),y;\lambda)}-1\label{eq:equil_rate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Unlike the bond price 
\shape italic
schedule
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y)$
\end_inset

,
 which is a function of a potential choice 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

,
 the equilibrium interest rate is the single rate that is realized after the government has made its optimal decision.
 The following corollary describes its properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cor:rate_spike"

\end_inset

 The presence of boundedly rational lenders (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<1$
\end_inset

) can lead to equilibrium interest rates that are significantly higher than those under full rationality (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

).
 Specifically,
 for states 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,y)$
\end_inset

 where the optimal new debt level 
\begin_inset Formula $B'(B,y)$
\end_inset

 is beyond the critical threshold (
\begin_inset Formula $B'<\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

),
 the resulting equilibrium interest rate will be strictly higher than in the fully rational benchmark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proof-for-Corollary"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuition for Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:rate_spike"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 follows directly from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:price_drop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The equilibrium interest rate is determined not by the entire price schedule,
 but by the price of the specific bond 
\begin_inset Formula $B'(B,y)$
\end_inset

 that the government optimally chooses at state 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,y)$
\end_inset

.
 The government's choice,
 in turn,
 depends on the trade-offs presented by the schedule.
 If the government is not heavily indebted and faces a good income shock,
 it may choose a safe asset position 
\begin_inset Formula $B'>\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
 it benefits from the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

market optimism
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 region with a 
\shape italic
lower
\shape default
 interest rate.
 However,
 in adverse states (low 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and/or high initial debt 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

),
 the government has a strong incentive to borrow for consumption smoothing.
 This need may be so strong that it is optimal to choose a new debt level 
\begin_inset Formula $B'<\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

,
 effectively accepting the discontinuous price drop.
 In this PRO region,
 Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:price_drop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 mechanically leads to a higher equilibrium interest rate.
 Because the price drop can be substantial,
 my model predicts that bounded rationality can generate the kind of sharp interest rate spikes often observed during sovereign debt crises,
 a feature that is difficult to produce in the standard,
 smooth model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Threshold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The existence of the critical threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

 is central to the model's dynamics.
 A natural question that follows is how this crisis threshold behaves with respect to output.
 The next proposition establishes that the threshold is state-dependent,
 showing that the government can sustain a higher level of debt during economic expansions before triggering the PRO shift in lender beliefs.
 This provides a clear theoretical channel for why crises are more likely to be triggered during recessions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:threshold_monotonicity"

\end_inset

 The critical debt threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing function of current output 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\tilde{B}'(y)}{dy}<0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proof-for-Proposition4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The critical threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

 is determined by the beliefs of the boundedly rational lenders,
 which are based on the expected future output 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\rho}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the persistence of the income process (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

),
 a higher current output 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 leads to a more optimistic forecast for future output.
 A better future economic outlook increases the value of both repayment and default,
 but as established in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:default_income-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 it increases the value of maintaining market access (
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}$
\end_inset

) more significantly.
 Consequently,
 when today's outlook is good,
 the government can accumulate a larger amount of debt (a more negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

) before the boundedly rational lenders perceive the situation as unsustainable.
 In contrast,
 a low current income 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 generates PRO-constrained beliefs about the future,
 causing the crisis threshold to be triggered at much lower levels of debt.
\end_layout

