\begin_layout Paragraph
The Discontinuous Price Schedule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My main theoretical result,
 Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:price_drop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 posits that bounded rationality induces a sharp,
 endogenous discontinuity in the bond price schedule.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:price_schedule_lambda"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provides a visualization of this phenomenon.
 The figure plots the bond price 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y)$
\end_inset

 as a function of the next period's asset choice 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 for both high and low current income states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As predicted,
 the price schedules for the boundedly rational economy (blue and orange lines,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.5$
\end_inset

) are fundamentally different from their smooth counterparts in the fully rational economy (green and purple lines,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1.0$
\end_inset

).
 Consistent with Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:price_drop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 for low levels of debt (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 to the right of the drop),
 prices are higher under bounded rationality,
 reflecting the market optimism of lenders who ignore tail risks.
 At a critical debt threshold,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

,
 the price drops discontinuously.
 For all debt levels beyond this threshold,
 prices are strictly lower than in the rational benchmark,
 reflecting the PRO-induced repricing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore,
 the figure provides visual confirmation of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:threshold_monotonicity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The critical threshold at which the price drops is state-dependent.
 The drop for the low-income state (blue line) occurs at a higher asset level (less debt) than for the high-income state (orange line).
 This illustrates that the government can sustain more debt in good times before
\emph on
 triggering the PRO shift
\emph default
 in lender beliefs,
 consistent with the fact that crises are more likely to be ignited during recessions.
\end_layout

