\begin_layout Proof
The government defaults if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y)>V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

.
 The value of default,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y)$
\end_inset

,
 as defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:val_default"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 is independent of the current asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that the value of repayment,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

,
 is non-decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The Bellman equation for repayment is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{R}(B,y)=\max_{B'\ge-Z}\{u(y+B-q(B',y;\lambda)B')+\beta E_{y'}[V(B',y')|y]\}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c(B,B',y;\lambda)=y+B-q(B',y;\lambda)B'$
\end_inset

 be the consumption when repaying.
 The partial derivative of the objective function inside the maximization with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 holding 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 constant,
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial B}\left[u(y+B-q(B',y;\lambda)B')+\beta E_{y'}[V(B',y')|y]\right]=u'(c)\cdot\frac{\partial c}{\partial B}=u'(c)\cdot1
\]

\end_inset

Since the utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(c)>0$
\end_inset

.
 By the Envelope Theorem,
 the derivative of the value function 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V^{R}(B,y)}{\partial B}=u'(c^{*}(B,y))>0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}(B,y)$
\end_inset

 is consumption evaluated at the optimal choice 
\begin_inset Formula $B'^{*}(B,y)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Now,
 assume 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{1}\leq B^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{R}(B^{1},y)\leq V^{R}(B^{2},y).
\]

\end_inset

If default is optimal with asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{2}$
\end_inset

 at output 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y)>V^{R}(B^{2},y)$
\end_inset

.
 Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B^{2},y)\ge V^{R}(B^{1},y)$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{D}(y)>V^{R}(B^{2},y)\ge V^{R}(B^{1},y).
\]

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y)>V^{R}(B^{1},y)$
\end_inset

,
 which means default is also optimal with asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{1}$
\end_inset

 at output 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{D}(B^{2})$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{D}(B^{1})$
\end_inset

,
 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(B^{2})\subseteq\mathcal{D}(B^{1})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

