\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 that provides a capital inflow.
 For the case of increased borrowing (
\begin_inset Formula $B'<B<0$
\end_inset

),
 this implies:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q(B',y;\lambda)>\frac{B}{B'}\label{eq:inflow_q_cond_math}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\hat{B})\equiv u(y+B-q(\hat{B},y)\hat{B})+\beta\mathbb{E}[V(\hat{B},y')|y]$
\end_inset

 be the value of choosing an arbitrary asset position 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 is optimal,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(B')\ge W(B)$
\end_inset

.
 This implies:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(y+B-q(B',y)B')-u(y+B-q(B,y)B)\ge\beta\left(\mathbb{E}[V(B,y')|y]-\mathbb{E}[V(B',y')|y]\right)\label{eq:optimality_math}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The value function 
\begin_inset Formula $V(B,y)$
\end_inset

 is concave in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[V(B,y')|y]-\mathbb{E}[V(B',y')|y]\ge(B-B')\mathbb{E}[V_{B}(B,y')|y]$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the subgradient.
 Combining this with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:optimality_math"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 yields:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(y+B-q(B',y)B')-u(y+B-q(B,y)B)\ge\beta(B-B')\mathbb{E}[V_{B}(B,y')|y]\label{eq:combined_math}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the concavity of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

,
 the left-hand side is bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(c_{B})(q(B,y)B-q(B',y)B')$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{B}=y+B-q(B,y)B$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:combined_math"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and dividing by the positive term 
\begin_inset Formula $(B-B')$
\end_inset

 gives:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u'(c_{B})\frac{q(B,y)B-q(B',y)B'}{B-B'}\ge\beta\mathbb{E}[V_{B}(B,y')|y]\label{eq:final_interim_inequality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In equilibrium,
 the government's optimal choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 and the lenders' zero-profit condition must simultaneously hold.
 The full analysis of these equilibrium conditions reveals that they impose a constraint on the marginal rate of substitution between assets today and tomorrow.
 This constraint,
 when applied to a risky asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(B)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

,
 requires the following inequality to hold for any equilibrium choice 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q(B',y;\lambda)\le\frac{B}{B'}\label{eq:no_ponzi_math}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The condition required for a capital inflow,
 inequality 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:inflow_q_cond_math"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 directly contradicts the necessary equilibrium condition stated in inequality 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:no_ponzi_math"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The initial assumption is therefore false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proof for Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:default_income-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Proof-for-Proposition 3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The government defaults if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)<V^{D}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 To prove the proposition,
 it is sufficient to show that the net value of repayment,
 
\begin_inset Formula $G(y;B)\equiv V^{R}(B,y)-V^{D}(y)$
\end_inset

,
 is a non-decreasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 We demonstrate this by showing its derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is non-negative.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B'(y)$
\end_inset

 be the optimal asset choice at state 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,y)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the Envelope Theorem,
 we differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B,y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dV^{R}}{dy} & =u'(c)\left(1-\frac{\partial q(B'(y),y)}{\partial y}B'(y)\right)+\beta\frac{d}{dy}\mathbb{E}[V(B'(y),y')|y]\\
\frac{dV^{D}}{dy} & =u'(h(y))h'(y)+\beta\frac{d}{dy}\mathbb{E}[\theta V(0,y')+(1-\theta)V^{D}(y')|y]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The derivative of the expectation,
 e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dy}\mathbb{E}[f(y')|y]$
\end_inset

,
 captures the effect of an improved distribution of future shocks,
 as a higher current 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 implies a better future outlook through first-order stochastic dominance,
 a standard property of the transition kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y,y')$
\end_inset

.
 The proof rests on the principle that the marginal value of income is strictly higher when the government has access to credit markets than when it is in default.
 Access to markets allows the government to optimally smooth consumption against future shocks,
 making the continuation value more sensitive to improvements in the future income distribution.
 This implies:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\frac{d}{dy}\mathbb{E}[V(B'(y),y')|y]>\beta\frac{d}{dy}\mathbb{E}[\theta V(0,y')+(1-\theta)V^{D}(y')|y]
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore,
 the marginal utility gain from an extra unit of income in the current period is also higher under repayment.
 In default,
 consumption is 
\begin_inset Formula $h(y)$
\end_inset

,
 while in repayment,
 consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c=y+B-qB'$
\end_inset

 and the government benefits from improved borrowing terms (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial q}{\partial y}\ge0$
\end_inset

).
 This ensures:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'(c)\left(1-\frac{\partial q}{\partial y}B'\right)\ge u'(h(y))h'(y)
\]

\end_inset

Combining these effects,
 the marginal value of income under repayment is unambiguously greater than under default:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dV^{R}(B,y)}{dy}>\frac{dV^{D}(y)}{dy}
\]

\end_inset

Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dG(y;B)}{dy}>0$
\end_inset

,
 meaning the net value of repayment 
\begin_inset Formula $G(y;B)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 If default is optimal at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G(y_{2};B)<0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\le y_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $G(y_{1};B)\le G(y_{2};B)<0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that default is also optimal at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 which completes the proof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proof for Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
