\begin_layout Proof
The proof proceeds by first establishing the existence and uniqueness of the critical threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

 and then proving the three claims of the theorem.
 The perceived default probability is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:delta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The price is 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:qdelta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Comparing 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;\lambda)$
\end_inset

 to the full-rationality benchmark 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;1)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to comparing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y;\lambda)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y;1)=\delta_{r}(B',y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First,
 I establish the existence and uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

.
 From the proof of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:default_assets"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(B',y^{\rho})$
\end_inset

 is a strictly increasing and continuous function of 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

.
 In contrast,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{D}(y^{\rho})$
\end_inset

 is a constant with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

.
 Given standard boundary conditions that ensure default is certain for sufficiently high debt and impossible for sufficiently high assets,
 the Intermediate Value Theorem guarantees the existence of a unique value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

 that solves 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}(\tilde{B}'(y),y^{\rho})=V^{D}(y^{\rho})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now,
 I prove the three parts of the theorem.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $B'>\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

,
 the strict monotonicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{R}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{R}(B',y^{\rho})>V^{R}(\tilde{B}'(y),y^{\rho})=V^{D}(y^{\rho}).
\]

\end_inset

This makes the indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}_{\{V^{D}>V^{R}\}}$
\end_inset

 equal to 0.
 The aggregate default probability becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y;\lambda)=\lambda\delta_{r}(B',y)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<1$
\end_inset

,
 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(B',y;\lambda)\le\delta_{r}(B',y)=\delta(B',y;1),
\]

\end_inset

with equality holding if and only if the debt is risk-free (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}(B',y)=0$
\end_inset

).
 A weakly lower default probability implies a weakly higher price,
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;\lambda)\ge q(B',y;1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $B'<\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

,
 the same monotonicity implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{R}(B',y^{\rho})<V^{R}(\tilde{B}'(y),y^{\rho})=V^{D}(y^{\rho}),
\]

\end_inset

which makes the indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}_{\{V^{D}>V^{R}\}}$
\end_inset

 equal to 1.
 The aggregate default probability becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y;\lambda)=\lambda\delta_{r}(B',y)+(1-\lambda)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}(B',y)\le1$
\end_inset

,
 the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{r}(B',y)\le\lambda\delta_{r}(B',y)+(1-\lambda)
\]

\end_inset

holds.
 Equality holds if and only if default is certain even for rational lenders (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}(B',y)=1$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y;\lambda)\ge\delta(B',y;1)$
\end_inset

,
 which implies a weakly lower price,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q(B',y;\lambda)\le q(B',y;1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Finally,
 I establish the discontinuity at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}'(y)$
\end_inset

.
 The right-hand and left-hand limits of the aggregate default probability are,
 respectively:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{B'\to\tilde{B}'(y)^{+}}\delta(B',y;\lambda)=\lambda\delta_{r}(\tilde{B}'(y),y)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{B'\to\tilde{B}'(y)^{-}}\delta(B',y;\lambda)=\lambda\delta_{r}(\tilde{B}'(y),y)+(1-\lambda)
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<1$
\end_inset

,
 the left-hand limit is strictly greater than the right-hand limit.
 This discontinuity in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(B',y;\lambda)$
\end_inset

 implies a discontinuous drop in the price,
 with the magnitude of the drop being precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{(1-\lambda)}{\left(1+r\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof of all claims in the theorem.
\end_layout

